reviews.review_text: Cornell Preview Very, very nice.  Killer Music to start and then the show just flows on from there. Second set is a preview of great things to come on 5-8-77.

mercy! usually not too big on audience shows, but this one sounds decent and the setlist and playing is outstanding.  I had to grab it.  Thanks bud!

End of 2nd Set The end of the 2nd set from St. Stephen on is really good. The Not Fade has some great jams in it.
agreed I agree completely with thebone.  schweet scarlet-fire!

One of the best of '77 If you love this band's music you must hear the St. Stephen sandwich in the 2nd set here. The NFA>Stella Blue is incredible and the whole thing is just pure magic. Also the Scarlet>Fire is a great one, which is saying a lot considering the context of all the other great Scarlet>Fire's around this time. go to Dead.net or Amazon and get this one!!!

4th row right center I knew this show was damn good as I was there; I listened on the way home last night and I was howling at the end of Half Step. It's just sparkling, you can almost here the paint dripping from the ceiling.  Tuscaloosa 5/17, used to be my fav HS but I think this may nudge it out. Whatdaya think?  Peace brothers & sisters
Those who love '77 shows will greatly enjoy this one. It's a warm, good-quality AUD, very listenable.

Pally two
Second night of the revered Palladium run and best overall. As good as it is, it only barely stands above the rest of the run, and as just another show in Apr/May '77. First Set. Music Never Stopped is a crazy-good, crystalline creator for the show. Surprisingly then, Bertha is kind of mellow. Though I claim this It's All Over Now as a fave, admittedly it kind of doesn't go anywhere, though smooth. See what you think. The OFF cuts the tech patter and Bobby's ruse "this is our first time in New York". Deal is just another great spring '77, w/good Donna. The bottle/jaw M&MU is excellent, with Jer adding random rhythm in between leads; and listen to the interplay on Peggy-O, especially Bobby. Looks Like Rain is the generic '77, but Mississippi Half-Step must be heard to be believed. Again, check out Phil & Bobby behind Jer. A basic Berry for break. Second Set. Scarlet Begonias has a stock jam, and it actually takes awhile for this set to take off like the first. Fire on the Mountain is the sixth one (the previous night, Scarlet went into GDtRFB). It's vampy and with a flubbed verse, but GOGD. They are game for Good Lovin' but again it's not quite nailed. Friend of the Devil is the turnaround and the rest is excellent. Estimated has a mellower start than usual but stays very tight; short solo but Keith is great and scope Bobby in the jam section. St. Stephen was a monster in its '77 arrangement, as shown here, and Not Fade Away has enough great parts to be an ace overall. Note how @7:50 the drummers quickly collude with Phil and force a unique jam...that breaks down...and builds back. One More Saturday is a hot cap on the set (complete on AUD only). Though this is the ninth Terrapin Station, it's only the second as an encore [albeit third as a final song]. It went into the encore slot again on 9/3 & 11/2 – but this is the big one. On the AUD you can tell this got very loud in there. 1st Set:  B+ 2nd Set: B+ Overall = 4½ stars Highlights: The Music Never Stopped – crystalline opener Deal – another great '77, w/good Donna Me & My Uncle – Jer adding random rhythm Mississippi Half-Step Uptown Toodeloo – focus on any one player Estimated Prophet – mellower, shorter, but so tight St. Stephen – at its new peak Not Fade Away – several great parts One More Saturday Night – hot cap Terrapin Station – nailed in the encore slot SOURCES: The AUD is an original Jerry Moore tape. The vernon_4949 has been remastered with love, however the first 18secs of Peggy-O are missing and there's a 4sec skip @12:30 in NFA that's not on the other copy. The whole show, in pristine SBD, is on Download 1, except with some tunings edited and part of Saturday Night replaced with 5/28.
